column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM XEROX CORPORATION LOCATED AT 800 PHILLIPS ROAD IN WEBSTER, NY TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 SOUTH STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS' CLEVELAND SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2940 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A SMALL HOLE IN THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE CLEAN UP RESIDUES. THIS CONTAINER WAS THEN SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. AN INSPECTION OF THE DAMAGED DRUM IDENTIFIED THAT AN UNKNOWN OBJECT PUNCTURED THE DRUM ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE. ** PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF DAMAGE OR LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. LOADING PERSONNEL AND DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSURE THAT ALL LOADING AREAS ARE FREE OF ANY DEBRIS THAT COULD PUNCTURE A CONTAINER.

CONSIGNEE ORDERED 4400 GALLONS. TANK SIZE WAS ONLY 3800 GALLONS. THEIR UNLOADER WAS CHECKING THE FILLING OF STORAGE TANK AND DRIVER WAS IN CONTROL OF DISCHARGE VALVE. THEIR UNLOADER WAITED TOO LONG TO INFORM DRIVER TO SHUT OFF WHICH RESULTED IN STORAGE TANK TO OVERFLOW. DRIVER BLED OFF AIR PRESSURE FROM CARGO TANK, CLOSED VALVES, BROKE CONNECT ON FOUR BOLT FLANGE, DRAINED PRODUCT IN HOSE INTO BUCKET AND RETURNED BALANCE OF LOAD TO JONES-HAMILTON. THEIR UNLOADER NEUTRALIZED CONTAINED PRODUCT AND TOLD DRIVER HE WOULD CLEAN IT UP AFTER NEUTRALIZATION.

DRIVER CONNECTED PRODUCT HOSE FROM OUR CARGO TANK TO CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK AND PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER PRODUCT. HE INADVERTENTLY HAD THE PRODUCT PUMP TURNING AND WRONG DIRECTION SO INSTEAD OF PUSHING PRODUCT FROM OUR CARGO TANK TO CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK, HE WAS PULLING PRODUCT FROM CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK INTO OUR CARGO TANK. OUR CARGO TANK BECAME FULL AND PRODUCT SPILLED OUT THROUGH THE VENT SYSTEM. CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK WAS EQUIPPED WITH A ONE WAY FIRE VALVE THAT SHOULD HAVE PREVENTED PRODUCT FROM BEING REMOVED FROM TANK. THE SAFETY MECHANISM OF THIS VALVE HAD BEEN REMOVED THEREBY ALLOWING PRODUCT TO FLOW BOTH DIRECTIONS AND ALLOWING OUR PUMP TO PULL PRODUCT FORM STORAGE TANK. IN ADDITION OUR CONTROLS BEEN CORRECTED OR IS BEING CORRECTED ON ALL VEHICLES. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. NO FURTHER ACTION IS EXPECTED AT THIS TIME.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1320 HRS, FRIDAY, NOV 8, 1996, A CONRAIL SUPERINTENDENT NOTICED THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR RTMX 2001 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID, SOLUTION LEAKING FROM THE SUMP.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1352 HOURS, THE BUFFALO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ALERTED.  AT APPROXIMATELY, 1356 HOURS, BATTALION CHIEF ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND AT APPROXIMATELY 1440 HOURS, AN ENVIRONMENTAL SPILL CONTRACTOR ARRIVED.  BOTH THE FIRE DEPT AND THE SPILL CONTRACTOR STOPPED THE LEAK BY PLACING A WOOD CONE PLUG IN THE HOLE AND WRAPPED A NEOPRENE PATCH AROUND THE WOOD CONE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HOURS THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS, PRESSURE VESSEL SERVICE (CONSIGNEE) ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1950 HOURS TRANSFER OF LADING COMMENCED INTO FIVE HIGHWAY TRUCKS.  TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AT 0230 HOURS ON SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 9, 1996.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HRS, EPS CLEANED AND NEUTRALIZED THE INTERIOR OF THE TANK CAR.  THE HOLE WAS PATCHED WITH AN EPOXY METAL.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT HOLE IN SUMP WAS CREATED BY PRODUCT.  CAR RETURNED HOME SHOPPED.  ** ALL CONRAIL EMPLOYEES (APPROXIMATELY 100) FROM THE FRONTIER YARD CAR SHOP AND ENGINE HOUSE WERE EVACUATED.  NO EVACUATION OF THE PUBLIC WAS NECESSARY.
ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN CONTAINMENT BASIN.  TANK CAME FREE BUT THE PUMPAND VALVES OFF TANK OVERFLOWED.

(APPROX 1 QT) THE LIQUID WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE DRUM PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM, THE DRUM WAS DELIVERED BACK TO THE SHIPPER AND TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER DRUM AND WILL BE DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT RESPONDED AND APPROVED OF OUR CLEAN-UP. THERE SHOULD BE BASICALLY NO COST.  STATEMENT FROM THOM THOMAS - REGIONAL SAFETY SUPERVISOR - SLC.

BRADY.  SGT. BRADY ADVISED THAT DRY ICE WAS IN THE BOX AND THAT THEY WERE UNDER THE IMPRESSION THAT DRY ICE WAS NOT REGULATED BY AIR.  I ADVISED HIM THAT DRY ICE WAS INDEED REGULATED BY AIR.  THE FREIGHT WAS FLOWN BY FEDEX FEEDED AIRCRAFT FROM THE ORIGIN TO THE ONTARIO RAMP.  I IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED FAA SECURITY IN LAX. I ADVISED THAT WE WOULD HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  ONCE THE INSPECTION IS COMPLETE THE DRY ICE WOULD BE REMOVED FROM THE SHIPMENT AND THE NON-HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSIDE THE BOX WOULD BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS THAT WOULD HAVE LED US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

THE HANDLER, DAVE CONKLIN TIGHTENED THE VALVES ON THE TWO CYLINDERS IN QUESTION UNTIL THE HISSING SOUND STOPPED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT ORIGIN.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device

ONE OF THE BOTTLES CAP SEAL HAD FAILED WHICH ALLOWED THE LEAKAGE.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE.  AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER AND THE INFORMATION OF THE MSDS SUGGESTS THAT THE MATERIAL SHOULD HAVE BEEN DECLARED AS A REGULATED FLAMMABLE LIQUID. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE WAS WESTBOUND ON US HIGHWAY 26 WEST OF RIVERTON, WYOMING.  BETWEEN MM 69 & MM 70 THE REAR AXLE BRAKES ON THE PUP TRAILER LOCKED UP.  THE PUP STARTED SKIDDING TO THE LEFT UNTIL IT ROLLED OVER AND INTO THE REAR FRAME OF THE FRONT TRAILER, GOUGING A HOLE IN THE FRONT OF THE PUP TRAILER, SPILLING PRODUCT ONTO THE HIGHWAY.  THE UNIT CONTINUED FORWARD WITH THE PAVEMENT GRINDING ON THE LEFT REAR OF THE PUP TRAILER.  WHEN THE UNIT CAME TO A STOP THE LEFT SIDE HAD A SMALL HOLE GROUND INTO IT BY THE PAVEMENT, CAUSING THE BALANCE OF PRODUCT ON THE PUP TO LEAK OUT.  THE CONCLUSION REACHED FROM THE EVIDENCE WAS THAT THE DRIVER PROBABLY DOZED OFF AND WHEN HE CROSSED THE BRIDGE, THE BUMP WOKE HIM UP.  HE SAW THE CURVE IN THE ROAD AND THE RED ROCK WALL AHEAD OF HIM AND HE TURNED TO THE RIGHT AND HIT HIS BRAKES CAUSING THE ACCIDENT.  THE JET FUEL RAN OFF THE PAVEMENT AND ONTO THE DIRT AT THE EDGE OF THE ROAD.  A SMALL AMOUNT (LESS THAN 500 GALLONS) RAN INTO THE WIND RIVER.  ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE PLACED DOWNSTREAM TO CATCH ANY PRODUCT.  THE SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND CLEAN SOIL PUT BACK.

FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDY DRI AND PLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE DAMAGED AND/OR LEAKING.

column168: OUR DRIVER HAD JUST LOADED AND HAD 77,000 LLBS. GROSS WT. HE THEN WENT TO THE NEAREST TRUCK STOP AND WEIGHED THE AXLES, SO THAT HE WOULD BE LEGAL ON THE SCALES GOING TO HIS DESTINATION. HE DISCOVERED THAT HE WAS 1000 LBS OVER ON HIS TRACTOR TANDEMS, SO HE RAISED HIS DUMP UP ABOUT 1/4 WAY IN THE AIR. HE WAS TRYING TO SHIFT THE WEIGHT TO HIS REAR AXLES. THE LOAD THEN BROKE LOOSE, SLIDING BACK AND UP OVER THE TAILGATE. THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TARP RIPPED FROM THE WEIGHT OF THE MATERIAL. MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANUP COMPANY RESPONDED WITHIN 1 HR. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PUT BACK INTO THE TRAILER. LOT WAS CLEANED UP AND DRIVER WAS REPRIMANDED.
column172: Highway hopper trailer for solid materials only

column168: ON NOVEMBER 20, 1996, THE VEHICLE/CARGO WAS IN THE NORTHERN ENERGY OFFICE/SHOP FOR REPLACEMENT OF THE HOSE REEL MOTOR. AFTER COMPLETING THE REPLACEMENT, OUR EMPLOYEES GREASED THE "CHICKSUN" VALVE BETWEEN THE PIPING AND THE HOSE. THE SEAL ON THE "CHICKSUN" VALVE FAILED ALLOWING PROPANE TO ESCAPE FROM THE HOSE. AN EXPLOSION OCCURED INJURING THREE EMPLOYEES AND DAMAGING THE OFFICE/SHOP. NO OTHER DAMAGE WAS DONE TO ANY SURROUNDING PROPERTY OR PEOPLE.

PALLET ON WHICH SHIPMENT WAS STACKED WAS NOT SUFFICIENT TO HANDLE WEIGHT OF SHIPMENT. DRUM HAD BROKE THROUGH BOTTOM OF PALLET EXPOSING IT TO FORKLIFT BLADES WHICH PUNCTURED 1 DRUM. SPILLAGE CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT AND SENT IN OVER PACK DRUM TO MFML FOR DELIVER TO CONSIGNEE. DOCKMAN RETRAINED IN PROPER PALLET PROCEDURES WITH FORK LIFT.
HOSE FAILED DURING UNLOADING PROCESS INTO DRUMS.
PETROMETER MALFUNCTIONED

column168: CUSTOMER TANK INSIDE BUILDING. THEY THOUGHT THEY HAD ENOUGH ROOM FOR PRODUCT. THEY DID NOT AND THEIR TANK OVERFLOWED.

column168: TRAILER ARRIVED INTO TERMINAL. EMPLOYEES NOTICED STRONG CHEMICAL SMELL. UPON INSPECTION OF TRAILER MANIFEST AND CONTE4NTS, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER HAD FAILED. UPON CLOSER EXAMINATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A SMALL PUNCTURE HOLE HAD BEEN SUSTAINED NEAR THE BOTTOM OF A DRUM. THIS DRUM WAS LOCATED ON THE LEFT OF THE TRAILER WITH OTHER DRUMS IN FRONT AND GENERAL FREIGHT LOCATED BEHIND IT. ALL DRUMS WERE PLACED ON CARDBOARD. DRUMS WERE BLOCKED IN WITH CARDBOARD, YET IT WOULD APPEAR THAT CARDBOARD WAS NOT ENOUGH TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF PUNCTURE WITH WHAT IS MORE THAN LIKELY A FORKLIFT BLADE.

column168: PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATIONS BECAUSE OF APPARENT LEAKAGE, STAIN AND ODOR. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS 4-32 OUNCE METAL CANS WERE FOUND INSIDE. ONE THE CANS WAS LEAKING FROM WHAT APPEARED TO BE EITHER A LOOSE OR DEFECTIVE TOP. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER THAT INDICATED THE MATERIAL TO BE A REGULATED CLASS 3 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELING ON THE OUTER PACKAGE TO INDICATE THE INNER CONTENTS WERE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION WAS ALSO NOT PROVIDED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS CONTACTED WHERE SPECIAL AGENT BART BARTANOWICZ WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SHIPMENT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY CONTAINED AND ALONG WITH PACKAGE PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACAKGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE/ODOR WAS NOTICED. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL SEVERAL PLASTIC INNER CONTAINERS. ONE OF THESE CONTAINERS WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY AND THIS RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY .5 LITERS OF THE MATERIAL. LABELS ON THE INNER UNITS INDICATED PETROLEUM DISTALLATES AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR AN MSDS. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DRUM WAS EVIDENTLY DROPPED CAUSING THE LID TO BREAK ITS SEAL AND THEREBY LEAKING. DG SPECIALIST WERE CALLED TO INSPECT THE PACKAGE. THE INFORMATION WAS TAKEN OFF THE DRUM. IT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED TO OBTAIN MSDS. THE MSDS SHOWS THAT THE FLASHPOINT WAS 126 F THEREBY MAKING IT A FLAMMABLE LIQUID PRODUCT AND IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN MARKED, LABELED AND SHIPPER'S DEC. PROVIDED FOR THIS SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO SUCH MARKINGS, LABELS, OR DEC PROVIDED. THE FAA AS WELL AS THE SHIPPER HAVE BEEN CONTACTED. THE FAA WERE HERE TODAY AND WENT AHEAD AND DID THEIR INVESTIGATIVE WRITEUP. THE PACKAGE IS AWAITING PAPERWORK AND AUTHORIZATION FOR MARKING AND LABELS SO IT CAN BE MOVED. IT HAS BEEN RELEASED BY THE FAA.

THE CONSIGNEE'S HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED. CSXT RESPONDED A HAZ MAT MANAGER FROM WALBRIDGE. OH, FOR UNLOADING. AT 1700HRS, THE CONSIGNEE'S TEAM STOPPED THE LEAK BY APPLYING A MODIFIED C KIT. THE FIRE DEPT RELEASED THE YARD AT 1735 HRS. CSXT OBTAINED AN EMERGENCY APPROVAL TO MOVE THE CAR TO BELPRE, OH. FOR UNLOADING. CSXT'S HAZMAT MANAGER & HAZMAT TEAM ESCORTED THE CAR TO DESTINATION.

AT THE BULK INTERMODAL DISTRIBUTION (BIDS) TERMINAL IN EVANSVILLE, IN. A TANKER TRUCK FOR ULRICH CHEMICAL WAS BEING LOADED FROM TANK CAR PROX 16075.  THE LOADER INFORMED THE TRUCK DRIVER THAT THERE WOULD BE A DELAY IN LOADING HIS TRUCK ACCT THEY HAD BLOWN THE RUPTURE DISK ON THE TANK CAR. A FEW MINUTES LATER THE TRUCK DRIVER MOVED HIS TRUCK WHILE THE LOADING HOSE WAS STILL CONNECTED. THE TRANSFER CONNECTIONS AT THE TANK CAR & THE TRUCK WERE BROKEN ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPILL FROM THE TRUCK AND FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR (CAR WAS BEING UNLOADED UNDER PRESSURE). THE VALE ON THE TRUCK WAS SHUT & THE LEAK FROM THE TANK CAR STOPPED WHEN THE PRESSURE BLEW OFF. LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED & A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO CONDUCT THE CLEANUP. THE SPILLED ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME. THE FIRE DEPT EVACUATED 2 NEARBY BUSINESSES AS A PRECAUTION.
T/C ACFX 95082 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM ITS TOP WHILE IN MOTION BY THE SWITCHING CREW. I RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE RUPTURE DISC. SHIPPER CONTACTED.

A TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN ROCKY MOUNT, NC. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. THE SHIPPER SENT A SPILL CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE CAR. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM GROUND THE MANWAY PLATE ACCOUNT OF A BAD GASKET. TWO OF THE MANWAY PLATE BOLTS WERE SHEARED OFF AND TH E8 INCH FILL HOLE COVER WAS LOOSE. THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE BOLTS, INSTALLED A TEMPORARY GASKET AND TIGHTEN DOWN THE FILL HOLE COVER. THE CAR RELEASED.

MCDONALD TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL, FIRE DEPT. ON THE SCENE. CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER, TL MURTA RESPONDED FROM CINCINNATI, OH. CSXT ALSO SENT CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR TO DO CLEANUP. MURTA FOUND THERE WAS NO GASKET ON THE 8 INCH FILL HOLE COVER. HE INSTALLED A TEMPORARY GASKET AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION MR. MCDONALD REPORTED THAT HE WAS HIT WITH A "MIST" AND HAD ONLY MINOR REDNESS ON HANDS AND FACE.

column168: WHILE MAKING A LEFT TURN ONTO PRITCHARD ROAD, A 330 GALLON POLY TANK SLID OFF THE BACK OF A CHEMICAL CLEANING TRAILER.  IT LANDED IN THE DIRT ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  A VACUUM TRUCK WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AND ALL OF THE LIQUID CAUSTIC WAS REMOVED.  ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERY, INC. WAS CONTRACTED TO REMOVE AND DISPOSE OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  THE FLORIDA BUREAU OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR WAS ON SITE AND OVERSAW THE REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES.  REPORTS WERE MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT #367579), DEPT. OF PUBLIC WORKS, REGULATORY AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, AND BUREAU OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE.

CARGO TANK WAS PARKED ON AN INCLINE WHILE LOADING.  THE CARGO TANK WAS EQUIPPED WITH BOTH A SIDE AND FRONT CARGO TANK MOUNTED LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE FOR SAFE LOADING WHILE PARKED ON AN INCLINE.  DRIVER MONITORED ONLY THE FRONT TANK GAUGE DURING THE LOADING PROCESS WHICH REFLECTED A SMALLER LOADED VOLUME AS COMPARED TO THE ACTUAL LOADED VOLUME ALLOWING THE TANK TO OVERFLOW.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS BIOREMEDIATED ON SITE.  DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REMINDED THAT DURING A LOADING OPERATION WITH A CARGO TANK PARKED ON AN INCLINE THAT SPECIAL CARE SHOULD BE GIVEN TO MONITORING EACH LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE AND THE EFFECT OF THE CARGO TANK INCLINE ON THE GAUGES.

(A - E) SEA-LAND SERVICE, INC. ISSUED A BILL OF LADING FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF THIS CARGO.  SEA-LAND CONTRACTED WITH COLUMBIA COASTAL TRANSPORTS, INC. TO TRANSPORT THE CARGO ON THE HOUSTON TO NEW ORLEANS LEG OF THE CARRIAGE. THE CARGO WAS LOADED ABOARD COLUMBIA'S BARGE, THE POUNCE TRADER, AT HOUSTON AND SECURED WITH EQUIPMENT SUPPLIED BY COLUMBIA, TO THE SATISIFICATION OF THE MASTER OF THE M/V ALICE MORAN, THE TUG WHICH TOWED THE BARGE.  THE M/V ALICE MORAN WAS CHARTERED BY COLUMBIA COASTAL FROM MORAN TOWING AND TRANSPORTATION CO., INC.  ALL DECISION REGARDING DEPARTURE TIME, ROUTE AND NAVIGATION OF THE TUG AND TOW WERE MADE BY THE MASTER OF THE VESSEL.  SEA-LAND HAD NO FIRST HAND INFORMATION WITH REGARING TO THE EVENT FOLLOWING DEPARTURE OF THE TUG AND TOW FROM HOUSTON, UNTIL THE FLOTILLA'S ARRIVAL IN NEW ORLEANS.  HOWEVER, REVIEW OF THE DECK LOG OF THE TUG ALICE MORAN INDICATES THAT 0603 HOURS ON FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 8, 1996, WHILE THE VESSEL WAS LOCATED AT LATITUDE 28 DEGREES 08.1N AND LONGITUDE 90 DEGREES 38.7W, THE MASTER OBSERVED CONTAINERS FLOATING IN THE WATER,  APPARENTLY WASHED OVERBOARD FROM THE BARGE POUNCE TRADER.  THE MASTER ALSO OBSERVED THAT THE CONTAINERS IN BAY 5 SEEMED "IN SOMEWHAT DISARRAY."  THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT, WHICH OCCURRED WHILE THE CONTAINERS WERE IN THE POSSESSION OF A THIRD PARTY, IS UNDER INVESTIGATION AND AT THIS TIME NOT KNOWN.  THE MASTER OF THE VESSEL ELECTED TO PROCEED INTO THE PORT OF NEW ORLEANS AND THE TUG AND TOW WERE SECURED AT THE SEA-LAND TERMINAL, ALMONASTER DISTRICT, NEW ORLEANS AT 1450 HOURS ON SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 9, 1996.  WHEN THE BARGE ARRIVED AT THE SEA-LAND FACILITY, FOR THE FIRST TIME, SEA-LAND BECAME AWARE THAT THERE WAS LEAKAGE FROM SOME OF THE CONTAINERS.  SEA-LAND IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES AND COOPERATED FULLY TO CONTAIN THE LEAKAGE AND DISCHARGE THE CARGO FROM THE BARGE.

ALL DRIVERS IN ARCO'S FLEET ARE BEING TRAINED IN HOW TO CONDUCT A FUNCTIONAL CHECK OF THE INTERNAL VALVES ON THE TRUCK DURING THEIR SHIFT. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 3:45 ON THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 21 A CALL CAME INTO WEG ABOUT A SPILL THAT TOOK PLACE AT THE ZIPPO PLANT, IN BRADFORD, PA.  WEG DISPATCHED PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY TO THE SITE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT 7:00PM THE TRAILER HAD BEEN AIRED OUT AND WEG PERSONNEL ENTERED THE TRAILER UNDER LEVEL C PPE.  PERSONNEL FOUND THAT A DRUM'S TOP MANHEAD WAS LOOSE AND WHERE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED FROM THE RIM.  THE MANHEAD WAS TIGHTENED DOWN AND SECURED.  THE TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO THE LOADING DOCK, UNLOADED AND WE PROCEEDED TO DECON THE FLOOR WITH CITRIC ACID BOTH INSIDE AND OUTSIDE.  PH SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AND INITIAL RESULT WAS 12.5 AND AFTER TREATING WITH CITRIC ACID THE READING WAS 7.  MATERIAL GENERATED WAS DRUMMED AND LABELED.  THE MANIFEST WAS ALTERED TO SHOW AN ADDITIONAL DRUM BEING TRANSPORTED.  A NOTATION WAS MADE IN THE DISCREPANCY AREA OF THE MANIFEST INDICATING THAT THE DRUM HAD BEEN GENERATED FROM A SPILL CLEANUP.  THE TRUCK WAS RELOADED AND WEG DEPARTED SIGHT AT 9:30PM.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS WEST BOUND ON NARROW TWO LANE ROAD WHEN THE RIGHT FRONT WHEEL SLIPPED OFF OF EDGE OF PAVEMENT. DRIVER OVER CORRECTED, CAUSING VEHICLE TO CROSS ROAD TO THE LEFT AND GO OFF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. ATTEMPTING TO GET BACK ON THE ROAD, THE DRIVER STEERED TO THE RIGHT, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN. (A SKETCH OF THE ACCIDENT IS ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT). THE CARGO TANK DID NOT RUPTURE OR LEAK PRODUCT. THE LOSS OF PRODUCT OCCURRED WHEN HOSES WERE DISCONNECTED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK. THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS CLEANED UP ACCORDING TO STATE GUIDELINES FOR PETROLEUM SPILLS. LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED BY TELEPHONE OF THE ACCIDENT AND RELEASE OF 25 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.

THE SITE WAS CLEANED BY BEN'S TRUCK AND EQUIPMENT AND CONTAMINATED SOIL AND SLUDGE WAS TAKEN TO CHICO DRAIN OIL SERVICE INC. 1618 E. 5TH STREET, CHICO, CA 95928. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO REDDING FREIGHT LINER WHERE THE TRAILER WAS TOTALED AND SOLD FOR SALVAGE AND THE TRUCK WAS REPAIRED.

THE DUMP TRUCK BOARD - SIDED US AT THE REAR AXLE AND FLIPPED OUR TRUCK OVER. THERE WAS 2200 GALS.  OF PRODUCT ON OUR TRUCK.  WE ESTIMATE ABOUT 500 GALLONS LEAKING (THROUGH THE HATCH COVERS) AND ALL BUT 50 GALLONS RECOVERED.  PRODUCT WAS PUMPED INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANKER DAMAGED VEHICLE RIGHT AND REMOVED. WHILE INSPECTING CARGO, DRIVER DISCOVERED LIQUID LEAKING FROM REAR OF TRAILER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED A DRUM OF CLASS 9 MATERIAL, OIL & WATER MIX WITH 500 PPM CADMIUM WAS LEAKING FROM A SMALL HOLE ATA DENT MIDWAY ON SIDE OF DRUM. DRUM WAS HALF EMPTY. ANOTHER DRUM OF SAME PRODUCT WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY FROM BOTTOM SEAM. THE CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED WHO IN TURN MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH A CLEAN-UP CREW. THE CLEAN UP CREW OVERPACKED THE 2 LEAKING DRUMS AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE GROUND. MATERIAL ON GROUND WAS CONTAINED ON ASPHALT AND DID NOT AFFECT ANY WATER. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED, REPORT NO. 368154. THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES AS WELL AS THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND TRUCK STOP MANAGER. NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

AMOCO'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND THEY APPLIED OIL ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE REMAINING GASOLINE ON THE PAVEMENT.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING A 50% CAUSTIC RAILCAR, THE UNLOADING HOSE RUPTURED RELEASING APPROX. 200 GALLONS OF CAUSTIC TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE CAUSTIC RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT FLOWED ACROSS THE SURFACE OF THE ROCK AND SOIL TO A STORM DITCH TIED TO A PROCESS SEWER.  THE ROCK AND SOIL AREA WAS FLUSHED WITH WATER.  TO PREVENT REOCURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT, WE DEVELOPED A PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE ROUTE TO CHECK CONDITIONS OF OUR UNLOADING HOSE ON A ROUTINE BASIS.  WE ALSO MODIFIED OUR CAUSTIC UNLOADING STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE.

THE WYMNE TRUCK DRIVER AND ONE OF OUR EMPLOYEE'S WERE LOADING. THE TRUCK AND THE TANK HAD MORE PRODUCT THAN WAS MEASURED. THE PUMP WAS SHUT DOWN AS SOON AS THE MEN SAW THE TANK WAS GETTING VERY FULL. THE OVERFILL WAS ABOUT 5 GALLONS. ABSORBENTS WERE USED TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. I REPORTED THE OVERFILL SPILL TO OUR CITY ADMINISTRATION FIRE CHIEF-NRS-EMA AND LOCAL DNR.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 4, 1996, A HOSE BECAME DISCONNECTED WHILE OFF LOADING A TANKER TRUCK AT THE FUELS FACILITY. APPROXIMATELY 60 GALLONS OF WASTE DERIVED FUEL WAS SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD. ALL FUEL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE FACILITIES SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. FOAM WAS IMMEDIATELY APPLIED TO THE RELEASE IN ORDER TO REDUCE VAPORS. IMMEDIATELY AFTER FOAM WAS APPLIED, HOLNAM'S EMERGENCY COORDINATORS WERE CONTACTED. VERBAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES. THE ENTIRE RELEASE COVERED AN APPROXIMATE 370 SQUARE FOOT AREA. EMISSIONS CALCULATIONS FROM THE RELEASED VAPORS ARE ATTACHED. THE WASTE CODES ASSOCIATED WITH THE MATERIALS ARE ALSO ATTACHED. THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY SECURED USING ABSORBENT PADS AND CLEANING SOLVENT. THE FUEL WAS CLEANED UP IN APPROXIMATELY THREE HOURS. ALL MATERIALS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WERE PLACED INTO DRUMS AND WILL BE SENT OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL. THE WASTE DERIVED FUEL WAS NOT KNOWN TO CONTAIN ANY EXTREMELY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES. NO INJURIES WERE INCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. NO ACTUAL OR POTENTIAL HAZARDS TO HUMAN HEALTH AND THE ENVIRONMENT REMAINS AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. NO EVACUATION WAS REQUIRED. NO CONTAMINATION OF ANY WATER BODY OCCURRED.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK INTO THE TANK TRAILER #9037 WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  (IT WAS NECESSARY TO PUMP THE UNLEADED GASOLINE INTO TRAILER #9037 TO EFFECT A TANK PRODUCT DESIGNATION CHANGE AT THIS LOCATION.  TRAILER #9037 WOULD ACT AS TEMPORARY STORAGE FOR THE UNLEADED GASOLINE WHILE THE PREMIUM UNLEADED GASOLINE WAS TRANSFERRED FROM ITS TANK INTO THE FORMER UNLEADED GASOLINE STORAGE TANK AND FINALLY THE UNLEADED GASOLINE WOULD BE TRANSFERRED FROM TRAILER #9037 INTO THE FORMER PREMIUM UNLEADED GASOLINE STORAGE TANK). WHILE ENGAGED IN THE TRANSFER ACTIVITY, THE PRESSURE HOSE RUPTURED, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE ON THE PAVEMENT AT THE STATION.  ALL BUT 5 OR 6 GALLONS OF SAID PRODUCT REMAINED IN THE AREA OF THE TRAILER AND WAS EASILY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE 5 OR 6 GALLONS THAT ESCAPED WERE RETRIEVED, USING ABSORBENT PADS, FROM THE DRAIN SUMP PRIOR TO ENTERING THE STORM DRAIN.  NO PRODUCT LEFT THE PROPERTY. MATERIALS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WERE LATER DISPOSED OF AS REQUIRED.

ON EVENING OF NOVEMBER 6, 1996 AT APPROXIMATELY 22:30 HOURS, THE OPERATOR AT THE GENEVA STEEL COKE PLANT BY-PRODUCTS PLANT SPILLED ABOUT 3640 LBS OF COAL TAR [COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, UN1993] WHILE LOADING RAIL TANK CAR ACFX 88690. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO EQUIPMENT. TO THE EXTENT POSSIBLE, THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECYCLED BACK TO THE PROCESS. COAL TAR THAT HAD CONTAMINATED THE SOIL WAS PLACED INTO DRUMS AND DISPOSED OF OFF SITE ACCORDING TO APPLICABLE REGULATIONS. THE OPERATORS HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES.

column18: LA REFINERY O 1600 W ANAHEIM S
column168: RUST INDUSTRIAL CLEANING SERVICES, INC., CONTRACTOR WORKING FOR UNOCAL 76-CARSON REFINERY, TRANSPORTING RQ WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, TOXIC N.O.S. IN A CARGO TANK (D.O.T. SPEC 307/312) FROM UNOCAL-WILMINGTON TO UNOCAL-CARSON. THE DRIVER/OPERATOR APPROACHED THE CARSON FACILITY GATE WHEN MATERIAL WAS OBSERVED ON THE GROUND, ORIGINATING FROM THE TRAILER'S LOADING/UNLOADING INTERNAL PRESSURE/VENT VALVE. THE DRIVER/OPERATOR APPARENTLY FAILED TO FULLY CLOSE THE VALVE AND CAP THE LINE PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION. REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES' HAZMAT TEAM, GENERATOR, TRANSPORTER AND CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE TRAILER WAS INSPECTED, THE VALVE FULLY CLOSED AND APPROXIMATELY 3 TO 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL RECOVERED AT THE SCENE. THE NRC PHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE AS REQUIRED WHILE SPILL RESPONSE WAS IN PROGRESS. SINCE THE INCIDENT, ALL MAINTENANCE RECORDS (CHP B.I.T. AND 49 CFR 180.407 CARGO TANK INSPECTION RECORDS) HAVE BEEN REVIEWED WITH NO DISCREPANCIES NOTED. SAFETY MEETING HAVE BEEN SCHEDULED WITH MANDATORY PARTICIPATION BY ALL SUPERVISORS AND DRIVERS TO DISCUSS THIS INCIDENT AND PREVENT ANY RECURRENCE OR SIMILAR RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DUE TO DRIVER/OPERATOR ERROR.

THE WECO WING UNION 2" FIGURE #206 CONNECTING OUR PIPE TO THE RAIL CAR HAD A FAULTY O-RING INSTALLED ON THE SEAT ALLOWING TDI TO LEAK FROM THE JOINT WHEN THE CAR WAS PRESSURIZED. AS SOON AS THE LEAK WAS NOTICED BY MR. STORES, HE SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF TDI BY SHUTTING THE VALVE ON THE RAIL CAR. THE ESCAPING TDI FORMED A PUDDLE UNDER THE CAR WHICH DUE LOW TEMPERATURES IMMEDIATELY FROZE. THIS PUDDLE WAS REMOVED AND PLACED IN CONTAINERS THAT WERE PROPERLY LABELED AND PLACED IN THE 90 DAY STORAGE FACILITY. FROZEN TDI RESIDUE WAS REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR WITH STEAM. THE UNLOADING OF THE RAIL CAR WAS CONTINUED TO COMPLETION THE NEXT DAY, SATURDAY 11-2-96 WITHOUT INCIDENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON NOVEMBER 6, 1996, WASTE MATERIALS WERE DRIPPING OUT OF BACK OF VAN HAULING DRUMMED WASTE.  SODIUM CHLORIDE SALTS AND WATER FROM INCINERATION PROCESS WERE THE MATERIALS INVOLVED.  THE MAXIMUM QUANTITY OF WASTE MATERIAL LEAKED WAS DETERMINED TO BE 5 GALLONS OF LIQUID, ASSUMING THE DRUM WAS COMPLETELY FULL.  THE DRUM CONTAINED 50 GALLONS OF MATERIAL AFTER THE SPILL.  THE ACTUAL AMOUNT SPILLED IS ESTIMATED AROUND TWO GALLONS BASED ON THE SIZE OF THE LIQUID PUDDLE.  THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM THE GENERATORS FACILITY TO  THE HIGHWAY 36 FACILITY BY TRIAD TRANSPORT INC.  THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED AT THE FLYING J TRAVEL PLAZA AT 198 E. MAIN IN LIMON COLORADO TO REFUEL. DURING A WALK AROUND INSPECTION THE DRIVER DISCOVERED LIQUIDS DRIPPING OUT OF THE BACK OF THE VAN.  HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED HIS DISPATCH AND ROLLINS HIGHWAY 36.  HIGHWAY 36 WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AT 0945 HRS ON 11/6/96. ROLLINS-HIGHWAY 36 DISPATCHED A SPILL CLEAN UP TEAM, CONSISTING OF DON BARNES AND TARRY CLUFF.  THE SPILL CLEAN UP CREW ARRIVED AT THE SPILL SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30AM.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CONED OFF TO PREVENT UNAUTHORIZED ENTRANCE. THE DRIVER WAS WITH THE TRUCK AND HAD SPREAD ABSORBENT MATERIALS, FURNISHED BY THE FLYING J, ON THE LIQUID SPILL.  THE SPILL TEAM PLACED ABSORBENT PADS UNDER THE BACK END OF THE TRUCK TO CONTAIN DRIPPING.  THE MANAGER OF THE FLYING J AND THE LIMON POLICE DEPARTMENT REQUESTED THAT THE VANNOT BE OPENED UNTIL THE COLORADO STATE PATROL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM ARRIVED.  BILL MILLS FROM ROLLINS-HIGHWAY 36 ARRIVED AT THE SPILL SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 10:45.  AT THIS TIME A SMALL PLASTIC BUCKET WAS POSITIONED UNDER THE VAN TO COLLECT DRIPPING LIQUIDS.  AT 11:15AM THE COLORADO STATE PATROL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM ARRIVED.  THE LIMON POLICE CHIEF AGREED TO ALLOW THE COLORADO STATE PATROL(CSP) TO OVERSEE THE CLEANUP PROCEDURES. ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS COMPLETELY ON ITS SIDE.  THIS DRUM WAS SLOWLY LEAKING LIQUIDS FROM AROUND THE SILICON SEALED SAMPLING HOLE IN THE LID.  THE DRUM WAS UPRIGHTED AND THE OTHER DRUMS WERE REPOSITIONED AND THE LOAD LOCK REINSTALLED.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO ABSORB LIQUIDS FOUND IN THE PAN OF THE VAN.  THE BACK GATE ON THE PAN WAS MISSING FROM THE LOAD.  THE LEAKING LIQUIDS HAD RUN TOWARDS THE BACK OF THE VAN AND DRIPPED OUT UNDER THE VAN TAILGATE.  ALL ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO THREE 20 GALLON FIBER DRUMS. THESE DRUMS WERE PLACED IN THE BA

REEDER TIGHTENED THE VALVE BUT, WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE RELEASE.  THE SHIPPER, UNION CARBIDE WAS ASKED IF THEY WOULD SEND A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SITE. THEY DECIDED TO FURTHER TIGHTEN THE VALVE TO SEE IF THAT WOULD STOP THE LEAK.  THIS WAS SUCCESSFUL.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT WITHOUT DELAY.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT VERN LIBBY WAS CONTACTED BY DEBBIE MARTIN, SUPV. UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT, SEATTLE, WA. AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HRS., 11/11/96. SHE ADVISED, CONTAINER MOLU 273536 LOADED ON FLATCAR HS 903140, LOCATED IN RAMP #1 ON THE SOUTH END WAS LEAKING, THE FLATCAR WAS TURNING COLORS, AND A YELLOW/WHITE VAPOR CLOUD WAS FORMING BETWEEN CONTAINERS ON THE FLATCAR. FURTHER DEBBIE STATED SHE HAD RECEIVED NO DOCUMENTS FROM THE DRAYMAN (N.W. CONTAINER) TO INDICATE CONTAINER MOLU 273536 CONTAINED ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE SOUTHEND OF RAMP #1 AND #2 WAS IMMEDIATELY CLOSED DOWN AND ALL EMPLOYEES WERE ADVISED TO STAY CLEAR OF THE AREA. STEVE ANDERSON, N.W. CONTAINER, SEATTLE, WA. (206) 762-1007 WAS CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY. HE ADVISED HE HAD NO INFORMATION INDICATING THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. HE STATED HIS DRIVER HAD RECEIVED NOTHING A TERMINAL #5, SEATTLE TO INDICATE THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. HE CONTACTED T-5 AND WAS FAXED MITSUI O.S.K. LINES, IMPORT TRANSPORTATION ORDER SHEET, PO #00720413, DATED 11/06/96 LISTING NOTHING REFERENCE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. HE SUBSQUENTLY RECEIVED A FAXED COPY OF A DECLARATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS IN CONTAINER AND CONTAINER PACKING CERTIFICATE, FROM MITSUI O.S.K. LINES IDENTIFING CONTAINER CONTENTS AS 60 DRUMS, 19620 KGS., SULPHUR DICHLORIDE (LIQUID) IMCO = 8.0, UN NO. 1828, PACKING GROUP = PH I. STEVE STATED HE HAD CONTACTED DEBBIE AND MIKE BATES AT T-5 REFERENCE THIS MATTER. STEVE PROVIDED AN EMERGENCY TELEPHONE NUMBER ON THE DANGEROUS GOOD CERTIFICATE FOR THE CONSIGNEE JAMES RIVER CORP., CAMAS, WA. (360)834-3021. STEVE PROVIDED PHOTO COPIES OF ALL DOCUMENTS THAT WERE FAXED TO HIM. ** SAHM LIBBY CONTACTED MARGIE DAVIS, CHRIS NEWMAN, DOUG BETH, AND TOM FREEMAN, JAMES RIVER EMERGENCY SERVICES, CAMAS, WA. AND WAS ADVISED THEY WOULD NOT RESPOND, AS THEY WERE NOT IN POSSESSION OF THE MATERIAL. HOWEVER THEY DID FAX A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY SHEET FOR SULPHUR DICHLORIDE TO ME. SOLANGE YOUNG, MITSUI O.S.K. LINES, SEATTLE, WA. (206)464-3930 WAS CONTACTED REFERENCE THIS INCIDENT. ** SHE CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE, WA. (206)764-0441 TO HANDLE THE CLEANING OF FLATCAR HS 903140, OVERPACKING OF DAMAGED DRUMS, CLEANING OF CONTAINER MOLU 273536 AND TRANSLOADING OF CONTENTS. SHE ALSO CONTRACTED, PETER JOHNSTONE, ADMIRALTY MARINE SURVEYORS (NW) TO INSPECT THE DRUMS LOADED IN CONTAINER IN QUESTION. ** FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL'S RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AND PLACED ON PLASTIC. THE END DOORS WERE OPENED BY FOSS'S RESPONSE TEAM (IN LEVEL B PROTECTIVE CLOTHING) AND AGAIN SODA ASH WAS APPLIED IN THE DOORWAY AND AROUND A 55 GALLON DRUM LOADED IN THE CENTER OF DOORWAY, THAT APPEARED TO BE WEEPING AT THE BOTTOM WELD SEAM. THIS DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM WITH APPROXIMATELY 2" SODA ASH IN THE BOTTOM OF IT. THIS ENDEVOR STABALIZED THE SITUATION. HOWEVER FURTHER INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED ANOTHER DRUM HAD BEEN PREVIOUSLY OVERPACKED PRIOR TO ARRIVAL, SEATTLE, WA.

ON 10-19-96 AT APPROX 1130 HRS THE INBOUND YARD MASTER IN THE N. LITTLE ROCK YARD CONTACTED CTS MGR. M. KELLY AND ADVISED THAT A CARMAN WORKING IN THE YARD NOTICED A SMALL DRIP FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET ON THE TANK CAR GATX 87175. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE YARD KELLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SEEP OUT. KELLY TIGHTENED E VALVE HANDLE ABOUT ONE AND A HALF TURNS, AND THE DRIP STOPPED. NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE FOUND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TO ITS' DESTINATION. THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED BY PHONE.

ON THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 14, 1996 AT 1630 HOURS, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT E.R. FEDRICK, WAS ADVISED BY CTS MANAGER: TOM ROBINSON THAT HE HAD RECEIVED A REPORT OF TANK CAR GATX 16950 AT LONGVIEW, TX., LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY COVER. HE DROVE TO THE SCENE, LOCATED THE TANKCAR, AND NOTED THAT PRODUCT COVERED AN AREA ON THE TOP OF THE CAR. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE MANWAY COVER. EIGHT OF EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE. FEDRICK TIGHTENED ALL EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS. YARDMASTER MIKE RAGG ADVISED OF ACTION TAKEN AND NOTIFIED THAT CAR WAS RELEASE TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION. FEDRICK ALSO CALLED CHEMTREC AND ADVISED R. RICHARDS OF THE INCIDENT. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MERICHEM COMPANY, SHIPPING SUPERVISOR, JIM MILLER. HE WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN. CTS MANAGER TOM ROBINSON ALSO ADVISED OF CORRECTIVE MEASURES.

SPECIALIST CTS DICK TUFTS WAS CONTACTED AT 0100 HRS ON 11/22/96 BY MYO NATHAN OELKE, CEDAR RAPIDS, IA. ADVISING THAT UCLX30005 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR INTERMITENTLY. SPECIALIST TUFTS NOTIFIED REGIONAL MGR. CTS TOM ROBINSON AT 0130 HRS. AND WAS ENROUTE TO CEDAR RAPID AT 0145 HRS. SPECIALIST TUFTS ADVISED MYO OELKE THAT ETA WAS 0600 HRS. WHILE ENROUTE, SPECIALIST TUFTS CONTACTED CHEMTREC, CHRIS, AT 0150 HRS AND REQUESTED ASSISTANCE WITH SHIPPER CONTACTS. APPROX 0210 HRS., SPECIALIST TUFTS RECEIVED A CALL FROM VULCAN CHEMICALS REPRESENTATIVE RUSS KREMER, WICHITA, KS. ADVISING THAT CAR WAS LOADED AT MONSANTO, SAUGET, IL. AND THAT VULCAN WAS THE OWNER. SPECIALIST TUFTS ADVISED THAT HE WAS ENROUTE TO SCENE AND WOULD ASSESS PROBLEM UPON ARRIVAL AT APPROX 0600 HRS. HE ADVISED FURTHER, SPECIALIST TUFTS ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS BEING ISOLATED. APPROX 0330 HRS, SPECIALIST TUFTS WAS CONTACTED BY MYO OELKE WHO ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON TRACK 22 AND THAT THERE WAS A POTENTIAL THAT AT THIS LOCATION THE PUBLIC COULD BE EXPOSED DUE TO A ROAD THAT RUNS ADJACENT TO TRACK 22. SPECIALIST TUFTS REQUESTED MYO OELKE CONTACT THE LOCAL POLICE DEPARTMENT AND REQUESTED THAT THE ROAD BE BLOCKED OFF TO TRAFFIC. MYO OELKE AGAIN CONTACTED SPECIALIST TUFTS AT 0350 HRS AND ADVISED THAT POLICE AND FIRE DEPTS WERE ON THE SCENE AND WERE PLACING BARRIER TAPE ACROSS ROADWAY. SPECIALIST TUFTS CONTACTED IOWA DNR AT 0420 HRS TO MAKE STATE REPORT OF SPILL. DNR CONTACTED CEDAR RAPIDS FIRE WHO ADVISED THAT THEY BELIEVED THAT THE CAR HAD A BLOWN FRANGIBLE DISC. FIRE HAD RETURNED TO QUARTERS. DNR CALLED SPECIALIST TUFTS TO ADVISE SAME. ** SPECIALIST TUFTS ARRIVED AT CEDAR RAPIDS AT 0600 HRS AND NOTED THE CAR INVOLVED, UCLX30005 HAD A BLOWN 100 LB OSECCO FRANGIBLE DISC. USING APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE GEAR, SPECIALIST TUFTS REPLACED THE DISC, USED A MIXTURE OF BAKING SODA AND WATER TO NEUTRALIZE THE RESIDUE ON THE CAR AND RELEASED THE CAR TO DESTINATION. SPECIALIST TUFTS MET WITH THE SWITCH CREWS INVOLVED AND ASSURED THEM THAT THE PROBLEM WAS RESOLVED. MYO OELKE ADVISED THAT CREW MEMBERS HAD COMPLAINED OF THROAT IRRITATION HOWEVER NO COMPLAINTS WERE MADE TO SPECIALIST TUFTS CONCERNING ANY PROBLEMS EXPERIENCED BY THE SWITCH CREW. MYO OELKE THAT HE HAD OFFERED TO TAKE ANYONE NEEDING MEDICAL ATTENTION TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT, HOWEVER, NONE THOUGHT IT WAS NECESSARY. SPECIALIST TUFTS CONTACTED MR. KREMER, VULCAN AND ADVISED CAR WAS SECURE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 112296 AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 PM MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MYO MALCOLM HAMFF. HE REPORTED THE CREW SMELLED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA IN THE AREA OF THIS CAR. REEDER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND OBSERVED A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD OVER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. REEDER OPENED THE HOUSING COVER AND OBSERVED LIQUID AMMONIA NEAR THE A END LIQUID VALVE. REEDER CHECKED TO MAKE CERTAIN THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE PLUG TIGHT, HOWEVER, THIS DID NOT STOP THE LEAK. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ASKED TO SEND A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE. EDWARD LUX WAS DISPATCHED FROM THE HOUSTON AMMONIA TERMINAL. column168: DURING THE SORT THIS MORNING THE BOX WAS DROPPED AND UPON IMPACT WITH THE CEMENT FLOOR THE BOX RIPPED OPEN.  THE INNER CONTENTS WERE OF A PERSONAL NATURE (CLOTHES, ETC.) AND IN ADDITION WAS A COLT .45 AND TEN LIVE POUNDS OF AMMUNITION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  I ADVISED LAX FEDEX SECURITY TO HOLD THE FREIGHT IN THEIR SAFE UNTIL IT COULD BE INSPECTED BY FAA SECURITY.  I THEN NOTIFIED FAA SECURITY IN LAX. WE WILL HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING THEIR INSPECTION.  I CALLED THE SHIPPER/RECIPIENT AND ADVISED THAT WE HAD FOUND HIS WEAPON AND THAT FAA HAD ASKED THAT WE HOLD IT FOR THEM.  UPON APPRISING MR. PARRIS OF THE SITUATION, HE ADVISED THAT HE HAD SHIPPED THIS WITH THE POSTAL SERVICE AND FEDEX IN THE PAST AND THAT WE HAD NEVER ADVISED HIM THAT HE COULD NOT DO THIS LEGALLY.  MR. PARRIS WAS EXTREMELY UPSET THAT WE (FEDEX) WOULD TAKE HIS PACKAGE WITHOUT TELLING HIM IT WAS ILLEGAL.  HE ALSO ADVISED THAT OUR CONDUCT WAS UNACCEPTABLE (BY NOTIFYING FAA BEFORE WE CALLED HIM TO RECITIFY IT).  MR. PARRIS WAS VERY VERBALLY ABUSIVE AND WAS UNCOOPERATIVE WHEN QUERIED AS TO A FUTURE DISPOSITION.  IF MR. PARRIS WILL NOT PICK UP HIS WEAPON AND BULLETS FROM LA FEDEX, THEY WILL BE TURNED OVER TO THE LOS ANGELES POLICE DEPT.

FEDEX WAS NOTIFIED AFTER DELIVERY OF PACKAGE THAT IT WAS CONTAMINATED. COURIER WAS SENT BACK ALONG WITH VAN AND BOTH FOUND TO HAVE SOME CONTAMINATION AND WERE DECONTAMINATED.  DUPONT NOTIFIED AND SENT PERSONNEL TO SYNCOR ALONG WITH DR ROY PARKER FROM FEDEX.  FLORIDA STATE DEPT OF HEALTH SENT OUT TEAMS TO THE RAMP IN JACKSONVILLE TO INSPECT AND MONITOR THE AIRCRAFT THAT THE PACKAGE CAME FROM MEMPHIS TN.  ANOTHER TEAM WENT TO THE GAINESVILLE FEDEX STATION AND MONITORED THE TRUCK AND CONTAINERS THAT DELIVERED THE PACKAGE FROM JACKSONVILLE AND THE STATION BELTS, PULLEYS AND EQUIPMENT WHERE THE PACKAGE TRAVELED.  ALL INSPECTIONS CAME UP NEGATIVE. THE HUB IN MEMPHIS WAS INSPECTED BY FEDEX SAFETY PERSONNEL TO COVER THE INBOUND SLIDES AND BELTS FROM BOSTON AND THE OUTBOUND SLIDES AND BELTS TO JACKSONVILLE.  RESULTS AGAIN WERE NEGATIVE.  AT THIS POINT NOBODY KNOWS HOW THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAMINATED.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGE OR ANY EVIDENCE TO SHOW THAT THE PACKAGE FAILED IN ANY WAY.  DUPONT IS STILL INVESTIGATING.  THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED AND THIS EVENT WAS REPORTED ON THE NRC DAILY EVENT REPORT.  THERE IS NO FURTHER INFORMATION AVAILABLE ABOUT THE PACKAGE IN REGARDS TO ITS MARKINGS AS IT WAS IN THE POSSESSION OF THE RECIPIENT AND NOW BACK AT DUPONT.

column168: TRUCK ROUTE EX864 HAD MADE A DIRECT PICKUP FROM THE CUSTOMER COLDWATER CREEK AT SANDPOINT, IDAHO AND THEN WENT DIRECTLY TO THE SEATTLE RAMP FOR OFFLOADING. AS THE TRAILER WAS BEING OFFLOADED THE CLOSER TO THE BACK THEY GOT THE MORE THEY SMELLED A SULPHUR ODOR COMING FROM THE FREIGHT. WHEN THEY GOT TO THE PACKAGE THEY FOUND IT WAS MOLDERING AT THE CORNERS AND NOTICED A LITTLE SMOKE COMING FROM THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WAS EXTINGUISED AND REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE AND THEN OPENED FOR INSPECTION. IT WAS AT THIS POINT THAT IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN FOUR PACKS OF STRIKE ANYWHERE MATCHES. THEY CONTACTED THE ON CALL DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST WHO WAS ME. I IMMEDIATELY REQUESTED ALL CONTAINERS THAT MAY CONTAIN FREIGHT FROM THIS COMPANY BE DETAINED UNTIL CONFIRMATION OF ALL FREIGHT THAT MAY CONTAIN OTHER MATCHES MAY BE FOUND. THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AS WELL AS THE SHIPPER TO ADVISE OF THE FINDINGS. AIRBILL NUMBERS WITH THIS PRODUCT IN IT WAS REQUESTED, RECEIVED AND THE RECONCILIATION STARTED FOR ALL THE SHIPMENTS TENDERED WITH MATCHES. THERE WERE 55 PIECES AND ALL WERE RECONCILED BY THE FOLLOWING DAY. ONE PIECE DID MAKE IT THROUGH THE SYSTEM BUT WAS CAUGHT AT OUR GRAND RAPIDS, MICH, RAMP. IT WAS TRAVELING ON AIRBILL NUMBER 251687512. IT WAS OPENED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN ONE PACK OF MATCHES. PLEASE FIND ATTACHED THE RECONCILIATION OF ALL THE PACKAGES TENDERED TO US PLUS A LETTER OF CONFIRMATION FROM COLDWATER CREEK THAT THIS PRODUCT HAS BEEN TOTALLY PULLED FROM THEIR INVENTORY.

ON WEDNESDAY 11/26/96 MY FIRST STOP WAS PERRET'S DAIRY IN CALLAHAN, FL.  I WAS INSTRUCTED TO GO BACK DOWN THE DIRT ROAD AND FOLLOW IT AROUND TO THE BACK OF THE FIELD TO MAKE MY WAY AROUND TO THE REAR OF THE BUILDING WHERE ALL DELIVERIES FROM APPERSON WERE TAKEN.  IN THE PROCESS OF GOING AROUND TO THE REAR OF THE BUILDING I HAD TO CROSS A DITCH WITH RUNNING WATER IN THE BOTTOM OF IT.  I SLOWED THE TRUCK TO ALMOST A STOP AND ATTEMPTED TO CROSS IT.  THE REAR BRACES FOR THE LIFT GATE AS WELL AS THE LIFT GATE STRUCK THE GROUND APPARENTLY CAUSING THE TOTE TANK TO CRACK AND BEGIN LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM.  AFTER DRIVING 25 TO 30 YARDS I NOTICED THE FUME ESCAPING FROM THE TRUCK.  I IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE TRUCK AND WENT TO CALL THE PLANT MANAGER, JIM MASON.  BEFORE MR. MASON ARRIVED I HAD TO MOVE THE TRUCK AS THE COWS WERE IN THE FUME THAT WAS ESCAPING.  THE TRUCK WAS MOVED TO A CEMENT SLAB AND PARKED.  A WATER HOSE WAS PUT INTO THE TRUCK TO HELP WASH IT OUT.  WHEN MR. MASON ARRIVED THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE TRUCK WAS CLEANED OUT.  THE TANK WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRUCK AND ALL RESIDUE WAS NEUTRALIZED.  SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE ALL ACID ON THE GROUND.  THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE.
I RESPONDED TO A FLAMMABLE LIQUID USING THE STEPS ACCORODING TO THE RESPONSE SHEET. I ABSORBED THE LIQUID USING SOLUSORB. I THEN DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL USING DMP PROCEDURES.

WHILE DRIVER WAS FILLING TANK, OIL CAME OUT OF THE VENT LINE ON THE HOME STORAGE TANK BEFORE THE TANK WAS FILLED.  THE VENT LINES ARE NOT PROPERLY INSTALLED.  REPAIRS ARE TO BE MADE.  SOIL REMOVED FROM SITE.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 15, 1996, BODINE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (BODINE) RECEIVED A TELEPHONE CALL FROM MR. LEE LOURET, OF MANITO TRANSIT, CONCERNING A DIESEL FUEL SPILL.  MR LOURET REPORTED THAT A (MANITO TRANSIT) SEMI TRACTOR TRAILER HAD SLID OFF THE WEST BOUND LANE, OF INTERSTATE 74, 300 FEET EAST OF MILE MARKER 146, DURING AN ICE STORM.  MR. LOURET REPORTED THE DIESEL FUEL RELEASE OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 AM. APPROXIMATELY 1300 GALLONS OF FUEL HAD RELEASED INTO A DITCH, LOCATED ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE WESTBOUND LANE. AT APPROXIMATELY 9:05 A.M., BODINE DISPATCHED A SENIOR PROJECT MGR AND TWO LABORERS TO THE SITE TO DETERMINE THE VISUAL EXTENT OF THE CONTAMINATION, INITIAL CLEAN UP OBJECTIVES, AND TYPE OF EQUIPMENT AND MATERIALS REQUIRED TO COMPLETE THE DIESEL FUEL CLEANUP.  UPON ARRIVAL THE PROJECT MGR PROCEEDED TO MEASURE THE SPILL AREA, AND PHOTOGRAPH THE AREA FOR THE "BEFORE" PICTURES FOR THE PROJECT FILE.  THE CONTAMINATED AREA WAS APPROXIMATELY 225 FEET LONG BY 8 TO 15 FEET WIDE.  THE PROJECT MGR DETERMINED A VACUUM TRUCK WOULD BE NEEDED TO REMOVE APX 5500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL REMAINING FROM THE DAMAGED TANKER, AND 1300 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL FROM THE DITCH. ************* FOLLOWING THE SITE INSPECTION BODINE PERSONNEL PROCEEDED WITH THE INITIAL CLEANUP OF THE SPILL.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF DIESEL FUEL WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH WITH ABSORBENT PADS, AND PLACED IN 6-MIL POLY DISPOSAL BAGS.  PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND MISCELLANEOUS DEBRIS WERE ALSO PLACED IN THE BAGS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM, BODINE'S VACUUM TRUCK ARRIVED AND BEGAN TO REMOVE THE REMAINING DIESEL FUEL FROM THE WRECKED TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT WAS VACUUMED INTO BODINE'S VACUUM TRUCK AND TRANSFERRED INTO A (STANDBY) MANITO TANKER.  BODINE PERSONNEL PROCEEDED TO VACUUM THE REMAINING 1300 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL FROM THE DITCH.  THE DIESEL FUEL VACUUMED FROM THE DITCH WAS TRANSPORTED TO BEAVER OIL IN HODGKINS, IL. BODINE TRANSPORTED THE DIESEL FUEL UNDER IL MANIFEST #IL 3677278.  A COPY OF THE MANIFEST IS ATTACHED IN APPENDIX D. **************** FOLLOWING INITIAL CLEANUP, A COST ESTIMATE WAS CALCULATED BY BODINE BASED ON OBSERVATIONS FROM THE SITE VISIT AND SIMILAR CLEANUPS. IT APPEARED THAT APPX 8-10 SEMI-DUMP TRUCKS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WOULD BE REQUIRED TO BE DISPOSED OF AT A SPECIAL WASTE LANDFILL.  IN ADDITION, 8-10 LOADS OF FILL DIRT WOULD BE NEEDED TO RESTORE THE SITE.  THE BODINE PROJECT MGR CONTACTED THE CLINTON LANDFILL LOCATED SOUTHWEST OF THE PROJECT SITE IN CLINTON, IL.  A VERBAL REQUEST WAS INITIATED FOR THE LANDFILL TO APPLY TO THE EPA'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNIT (ERU) FOR AN EMERGENCY DISPOSAL PERMIT TO BE AUTHORIZED FOR THIS SITE. THE APPROVAL FOR THE  EMERGENCY PERMIT AND ASSOCIATED AUTHORIZATION NUMBER WAS RECEIVED ON NOV. 18, 1996.  A COPY OF THE EMERGENCY SPILL RESPONSE REPORT IS ATTACHED IN APPENDIX C. column168: DEAN C COOPER, MGR, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS PAGED BY KAROL CARLSON, MGR, TERMINAL OPERATIONS, YERMO, CA, WHO ADVISED THE WEST END SWITCH CREW OBSERVED A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  TANK CAR GATX 22859 WAS RECEIVED ON INTERCHANGE FROM THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD AT COLTON, CA, 0024 HRS, TUESDAY, 11/26/96, AND ARRIVED IN YERMO ON THE CNYR-25, 0600 HRS.  MGR COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY AND DEVELOPED THAT THE CAR HAD ACTUALLY BEEN FOUND LEAKING AT 0120 HRS, WED, 11/27/96, WHILE BEING SWITCHED.  DURING THE SWITCHING OPERATION, TWO MEMBERS OF THE GROUND CREW HAD BEEN SPLASHED WITH THE PRODUCT.  BOTH SWITCHMENT IMMEDIATELY WASHED THE PRODUCT OFF AND CONTINUED ON WITH THEIR WORK, COMPLETING THEIR SHIFTS. THE SUPV, YARD OPERATIONS, HAD CALLED AND LEFT A MESSAGE ON MGR COOPER'S VOICE MAIL, AND DID NOT MAKE ANY FURTHER ATTEMPT TO CONTACT MGR COOPER. ********** MGR COOPER, IN COMPANY WITH ROBERT SPINKS, SPECIAL AGENT HAZ MAT, INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE CONTINUOUS BREATHER VENT.  THE VENT ASSEMBLY IS AN OLDER 4 PIECE ASSEMBLY WITH AN INSPECTION CAP; RETAINER COVER; BOWEL OR BASE PIECE; AND A 12 INCH FLANGE, WHICH MOUNTS DIRECTLY OVER THE 3 INCH DIAMETER RISER TUBE FROM THE CAR.  THE BOWEL ASSEMBLY BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THERE WAS A 1/4 INCH VOID BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OF THE BOWEL AND THE FLANGE.  IN ORDER TO ACCESS THE BOLTS FOR THE BOWEL ASSEMBLY, WHICH WERE MOUNTED INTERNALLY, THE FLANGE HAD TO BE REMOVED.  IN THE PROCESS OF REMOVING THE EIGHT 5/8 INCH FLANGE BOLTS, ONE BOLT WAS BROKEN OFF IN THE LOWER FLANGE.  THIS WILL HAVE TO BE DRILLED OUT AND REPLACED ONCE THE CAR IS SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS, AS THE APPROPRIATE TOOLS WERE NOT AVAILABLE IN THE FIELD TO DO THIS TYPE OF WORK. ******************* ONCE THE FLANGE WAS REMOVED THE 4 INTERNAL ALLEN BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED TO SECURE THE BOWEL TO THE FLANGE.  THE BREATHER VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED, WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO INSURE PROPER SECUREMENT AND THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES; AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: ON THE AFTERNOON  OF NOVEMBER 27, 1996, A RUPTURE DISC ON A RAILCAR UNLOADING LINE RUPTURED, AND THE SYSTEM EVACUATION HEADER WAS CHARGED WITH CHLORINE.  THE AMOUNT OF CHLORINE, WHICH COULD NOT BE ABSORBED BY THE EVACUATION LINE SCRUBBER, WAS EMITTED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE RAILCAR WAS VENTED TO THE SCRUBBER FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES. HOWEVER, DUE TO THE VARIOUS CHEMICAL REACTIONS WHICH OCCURED IN THE SYSTEM, THE RELEASE DURATION FROM THE SCRUBBER TANK AND SCRUBBER BUILDING LASTED MOER THAT 50 MINUTES. TWO BOWATER EMPLOYEES WERE SENT TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE RELEASED THE SAME DAY. BOWATER EMPLOYEES ACTED PROMPTLY TO SHUT OFF THE UNLOADING RAILCAR.  ALSO, A VALVE ON THE EVACUATION LINE WAS AUTOMATICALLY THROTTLED BACK BY THE SYSTEM.  THE THROTTLED VALVE REDUCED THE AMOUNT OF CHLORINE CHARGED TO THE SCRUBBER AND THUS REDUCED THE RELEASE. THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS ARE BEING TAKEN TO REDUCE THE POTENTIAL OF FUTURE EPISODES OF THIS NATURE: 1.  THE VALVE WHICH WAS INADVERTENTLY PLACED IN FRONT OF THE HIGH PRESSURE INTERLOCK SWITCH HAS BEEN REMOVED.  THIS WILL ALLOW THE SWITCK TO PROPERLY SHUT THE RAILCAR OFF WHEN HIGH PRESSURE IS DETECTED IN THE EVACUATION HEADER; 2.  A THREE-WAY VALVE WAS REPLACED WITH A SPOOL PIECE, AND THE CIRCULATING TANK LEVEL HAS BEEN RAISED TO 85%.  THESE ACTIONS HAVE RESULTED IN A HIGHER HEAD PRESSURE FROM THE PUMPS; 3.  THE HOLES IN THE EVACUATION HEADER AND THE FAILED RUPTURE DISC HAVE BEEN REPAIRED/REPLACED.  PIPING REPLACEMENT ON OTHER AREA OF THE SYSTEMS ARE UNDERWAY. THE RUPTURE DISC SUPPLIER WAS CONTACTED TO DETERMINE A CAUSE FOR DISC FAILURE;4. A PROCESS SAFETY ANALYSIS OF THE SYSTEM WILLL BE CONDUCTED IN DECEMBER 1996 BY BOWATER PERSONNEL.
